post_text:
White Oak ISD Community,

While it is difficult to predict the weather, due to Hurricane Laura, I am concerned about the possibility of heavy rain and wind tomorrow morning (Thursday) when our route buses will be on the road, along with the real possibility of an extended power outage on one or more campuses. After consultation with local officials and other area school districts, White Oak ISD has determined that it is the best interest of safety that we close school tomorrow, Thursday, August 27. We wanted to send this out tonight so that parents would have an opportunity to make any arrangements necessary. We apologize for any inconvenience.

Thank you for your continued support of White Oak ISD.

text: Due to inclement weather and possible power losses from Hurricane Laura, there will be no school tomorrow.

post_text:
From the Desk of Superintendent Brian Gray:

White Oak Community: Please know that White Oak ISD is monitoring the weather and Hurricane Laura closely. Depending upon where the hurricane makes landfall, and the timing, this will have a big impact on what happens in the state, and where it tracks northward. Please know that we are monitoring this VERY closely. As of now, it looks like a lot of rain is possible with high winds and if this comes to fruition, possible power issues. Once again, a lot depends on the location of landfall and timing.

White Oak ISD is in communication with DPS, the Weather Service, WO Emergency Management, and WO PD. We will monitor the situation closely. As of now, everything is on-go for school tomorrow (Thursday), but we will continue to monitor and adjust as needed. Any significant updates will be disseminated via School Messenger, Skyward Email, the website, blogs, and campus social media pages.

Thank you for your continued support of all things Roughneck!

Brian Gray-Superintendent of Schools
White Oak ISD
The Home of ROUGHNECK Pride

YOUTUBE.COM
Car Pick Up Procedures

White Oak Intermediate School
August 10 at 10:39 AM ·

There are some important CAR PICK-UP directions and changes this year.

-Both campuses will dismiss at the same time and changes to car pickup have been implemented for the safety of all students.
-You MUST have a Car Tag with your child’s name clearly visible hanging in your vehicle.
-ALL CARS must enter by the Administration building on the one-way Roughneck Drive.
-Cones will BLOCK all traffic that attempts to enter from behind the middle and high school blacktops. Those cars will have to turn around and enter the line by the Administration building.
-The entire parking lot has been made available for car pickup. Staff will be directing cars to form perpendicular lines of 8.
-We will begin calling Car Pickup at 3:20. Cars will not be allowed to exit onto Roughneck Drive until the buses have been loaded and have exited the bus line.

To avoid frustration, please watch, know, and follow the specific directions explained and shown visually in the video below.

post_text: Parents, this is just a reminder that you MUST HAVE a White Oak Car Tag hanging in your vehicle in order to pick up your child(ren) via the Car Pickup Line. This safety protocol is for the protection of our students, your children, and we will continue to be diligent with its enforcement. If you do not have a car tag or if you have lost your car tag, you will need to ask for another tag to be issued to you. They will be available from the intermediate staff on car pickup duty. Thank you for working together with us to keep our boys and girls safe.

post_text:
Please note that our drop-off time is 7:15 for both Primary and Intermediate students in front of the main entrance. We hope this early drop-off time and having buses unload at a different location will improve the flow of traffic and safety measures.

Teachers will be in their classrooms at 7:30 to receive students who choose not to eat breakfast at school or for students who are finished eating breakfast at that time.

Please note that students arriving after the 8:00 bell are considered tardy. A parent must accompany the student in the building to receive a tardy slip.

The cafeteria will serve breakfast for our Intermediate students from 7:20 a.m. to 8:00 a.m.

post_text:
ADDITIONAL SCHOOL SUPPLY DROP-OFF DAY – AFTER WORKING HOURS

In an effort to accommodate working parents, we will have an additional day/time for you to drop off school supplies, pay the $10 supply fee, fill out the transportation form, and receive car tags for your 3rd, 4th, or 5th grade student.

We will set up on Thursday, August 6th, from 6:00 p.m. – 7:30 p.m. in front of the elementary gym.

Coming by to fill out the transportation form will give teachers time to prepare their dismissal plans for each student and feel confident they know how your student is getting home.

We want to safely and efficiently dismiss our students and picking up the car tags in advance will allow for a smoother dismissal process.

Come see us tomorrow evening if you haven’t come by already!

Please watch the video below and follow the instructions for car drop off each morning.

Staff will be assigned to assist students in exiting the vehicles. Please make sure that your student has his/her backpack on and is ready to exit the car as soon as it comes to a stop. Because both campuses will be using the same route, it is imperative that students unbuckle, get out of the car, and step up on the sidewalk as quickly and safely as possible. We want to keep the car line moving so that no student arrives late to class.

post_text:
This year we have implemented some changes in our bus drop off and pick up procedures that we feel will prove to be more efficient and safer for our students. To avoid the congestion of cars and buses traveling the same route, this year all buses will drop off students in the morning and pick up students in the afternoon at the Primary Entrance along the north side of the building. The video below shows the yellow bus and the route that will be taken to safely ensure that all bus riders get inside the building without needing to pass between any other vehicles. Please be patient with us as we try to navigate this new system and work through any needed adjustments.

Also, this year both the Primary and Intermediate campuses will dismiss together. Remember that this is the first time that some of the younger children have walked in a line and loaded a bus. The first week always takes longer to load the buses, therefore, students may arrive home a little later than expected. Rest assured that our transportation department will deliver your child safely.

post_text: Superintendent Brian Gray, district and campus leadership teams, and the Board of Trustees are working hard on school re-opening plans. post_text:
The Intermediate grade levels will be substituting a Valentine Party provided by the 3rd, 4th, and 5th-grade parents. There will be NO EASTER PARTIES FOR 3rd, 4th, or 5th-grade students because of the TEA State Testing Calendar that mandates the days allowed for STAAR testing. The normal party day would have been on the last STAAR testing day prior to the Good Friday holiday.

Parents will need to check with your homeroom teachers to make arrangements for the Valentine Parties that will take place on Friday, February 14th.

post_text:
January 30, 2020

Parents/Guardians:

This afternoon we experienced some electrical issues at White Oak Primary and Intermediate campuses. Currently, SWEPCO is on-site and working through the issues.

At this time we are expecting to have power restored and a regular school day tomorrow, Friday, January 31st.

If the issue is not resolved we will notify you by 6:00 a.m. in the morning.

Please check the campus Facebook pages, campus blogs and teacher blogs for notification and updates.

This would affect the primary and intermediate campuses only.

Thank you.

Mike Morrison

Interim Superintendent

White Oak ISD

post_text:
White Oak Intermediate

COME EARLY

on Wednesday, January 29th

White Oak Intermediate will have their first in-house UIL meet this Wednesday, January 29th. Even though not every student on campus participates in the competition, every student will be affected in some way on this day with the accommodations we’ve made to hold competitions in our own classrooms.

In order for us to get started with competition in a timely manner, we are asking that all Intermediate car riders arrive at school no later than 7:40 a.m. on this day. This will allow time to have ALL students in their designated locations. Students can be dropped off as early as 7:15 a.m. as outside personnel is on duty.

If at all possible, we would appreciate your help on this day. We are very excited to begin our UIL journey and look forward to many competitions for years to come!

Also, don’t forget this is an

EARLY RELEASE day as well. Both Primary and Intermediate will release at 11:30.

Let’s have some fun this last week before Christmas break. Teachers and students are invited to take part in some special Christmas attire.

Monday – Don that Christmas hat.
Tuesday – Wear your Pajamas to school. What???
Wednesday – Put your feet into the spirit with some Christmas socks.
Thursday – Wear your favorite Christmas shirt or Christmas colors.
Friday – Come ready to celebrate with your friends at your class party.
You do not have to participate. This is only to bring a little Christmas cheer into our building. We can’t wait to see what walks through the door next week.

post_text:
Teacher Appreciation Week
May 6th-10th

I would like to invite all students and families to show extra gratitude to teachers/staff during this week. Here are some daily themes if you choose to participate (participation is optional) . Just bring item(s) to your teacher each day. You can participate every day or choose which days to join in.

💜 Mrs. McClanahan
School Counselor

MONDAY- You make us BLOOM ⚘
Bring your teacher a flower (fresh, fake, or hand drawn), or something with a floral print

TUESDAY- Teachers are NOTEWORTHY ✎
Write your teacher a note to explain how she has impacted your life this year.

WEDNESDAY- Teachers help to COLOR our world! 🌈
Wear your teacher’s favorite color.

THURSDAY- My teacher's a TREAT 🍪
Treat your teacher to her favorite snack or beverage, homemade treats or candy.

FRIDAY- Thanks are in the CARDS
Bring your teacher a gift card from one of their favorite places.

post_text:
The State of Texas Assessments of Academic Readiness, or STAAR, will begin this week. On Tuesday, April 9th, our 4th grade will participate in the Writing STAAR, and our 5th grade will take the STAAR Math assessment. On Wednesday, April 10th, our 5th grade will complete the STAAR Reading assessment.

We encourage our students to:

Go to bed early.
Be on time for school.
Plan to bring your lunch from home that morning or purchase your lunch from the cafeteria on these two testing days. Food brought in for lunch will not be allowed for any grade level on testing days. VISITORS for lunch will not be permitted on campus on April 9th and 10th.
Students may bring one, sealed bottle of room-temperature water. Any other drink will not be allowed.
We are proud of our students and know that they are ready to show what they can do. Let’s stand behind them and show our support by making sure these tips are followed by all.

The meal will be served at 6 pm in the Secondary Food Service building. Please come and bring your spouse as our guest for a nice meal and plenty of time to fellowship with others in the community.
We are also asking our parents and staff members to help get the word out concerning this event. If you know someone who has served or is serving currently, please extend this invitation on behalf of all of us at White Oak ISD.
The Board of Trustees, faculty and staff at White Oak are grateful for the service and sacrifice of our service men and women! It will be our pleasure to provide this small token of our appreciation.

post_text:
School Holiday Monday, Sept. 3rd

School will be closed Monday, September 3rd. Enjoy the time with your families celebrating Labor Day. Talk to your children about Labor Day and what it means.

Labor Day is celebrated on the first Monday in September. It’s a day dedicated to the social and economic achievements of American workers. The holiday credits the contributions of the working class to the strength, prosperity, and well-being of our country.

Labor Day became an official national holiday in 1894. This holiday is usually celebrated with summer activities. Elementary teachers use this holiday to introduce the concept of Community Helpers to small children. Everyone plays a role or works a job that supports their community.

What role do you play in your community?

post_text:
Walkers

Amendment to Student Handbook as of 8-2-17

Beginning the 2017-2018 school year, and continuing into the 2018-2019 school year, we will not have the typical “walker” line as we had in the past. For safety reasons, students will NO LONGER walk to the MS/HS parking lot to be picked up.

If we have students that walk home, they will ride a bus to the Middle School and will be released to walk from there.

If parents have students at various campuses, the Intermediate student will need to be picked up through the car pick-up line, then parents may park at a different location to pick up their MS/HS student.

Employee’s children will ride the bus to the MS where a designee can meet them for pick up.

PLEASE READ THE STUDENT HANDBOOK for all school procedures and concerns.

The link also remains on the side of our blog. Thank you for supporting our plans to protect your children, our students.

post_text:
The State of Texas Assessments of Academic Readiness, or STAAR, will begin this week. On Tuesday, April 10th, our 4th grade will participate in the Writing STAAR, and our 5th grade will take the STAAR Math assessment. On Wednesday, April 11th, our 5th grade will complete the STAAR Reading assessment.

We encourage our students to:

Go to bed early.
Be on time for school.
Plan to bring your lunch from home that morning or purchase your lunch from the cafeteria on these two testing days. Food brought in for lunch will not be allowed for any grade level on testing days. VISITORS for lunch will not be permitted on campus on April 10th and 11th.
Students may bring one, sealed bottle of room-temperature water. Any other drink will not be allowed.
We are proud of our students and know that they are ready to show what they can do. Let’s stand behind them and show our support by making sure these tips are followed by all.

post_text:
Active Shooter Response Training

The Board of Trustees at White Oak ISD invites the community of White Oak to Active Shooter Response Training. The event will take place in the CC Simmons Auditorium on Sunday, March 11, 2018. The event will begin at 2:30 pm and end by 4:30 pm including a Q&A time at the end of the presentation.

The trainer will be Mark Seguin, TBG Solutions Inc. Tyler Texas. He recently provided training to all employees at White Oak ISD and we feel his message and insight will be beneficial to everyone in White Oak.

There will be an updated report by the district on the security measures in place at WOISD and our commitment to providing a safe learning environment for our students, faculty, and staff.

On behalf of the District, I hope to see you next Sunday.

Michael Gilbert

White Oak Schools

Beginning Monday, December 18, 2017, there will be a new traffic pattern around the High School to accommodate a construction zone in the north student parking lot (in red). Please take the time to review the map included in the message and make note of the following:
There will be no through traffic in front of the high school and parking in that area will be for teachers only. (in yellow)
Areas available for student parking are outlined in orange. Those that park across the street from the auditorium will have a crossing guard to ensure safe passage to campuses.
All High School student drop-off and pick-up will be in front of the Food Service building, and traffic is designated as one way from south to north (in green). **(Traffic coming from the north on White Oak Road are encouraged to drop-off in the parking lot across the street and use the protected crosswalk)
This traffic pattern will be in place until the end of August 2018. The district would like to thank you in advance for your cooperation and patience during the process of upgrading our facilities.

post_text:
During the last two days, there have been numerous reports of sick students. Some students have experienced symptoms such as high fever, cough, headaches, body aches, and upset stomach. Some students who have been taken to the doctor have been diagnosed with confirmed flu and strep. The school is taking extra precautions with:
*cleaning and disinfecting
*increased focus on hand washing and sanitizing
*frequent reminders of how to cough (into your elbow) to reduce the risk of spreading germs
*frequent reminders to not share drinks, food, pencils that have been in other's mouths, etc.
Parents, please help us control the spreading of these viruses by keeping sick students home until they are free of all fever for 24 hours. We appreciate your support.
text:
During the last two days, there have been numerous reports of sick students. Some students have experienced symptoms such as high fever, cough, headaches, body aches, and upset stomach. Some students who have been taken to the doctor have been diagnosed with confirmed flu and strep. The school is taking extra precautions with:
*cleaning and disinfecting
*increased focus on hand washing and sanitizing
*frequent reminders of how to cough (into your elbow) to reduce the risk of spreading germs
*frequent reminders to not share drinks, food, pencils that have been in other's mouths, etc.
Parents, please help us control the spreading of these viruses by keeping sick students home until they are free of all fever for 24 hours. We appreciate your support.

post_text:
White Oak Intermediate School has decided to join together with our high school to dedicate tomorrow as a “Blue-Out for Brock” day. Students and staff who wish to participate may wear blue tomorrow to show your support for this courageous little boy and his family. You are also invited and encouraged to take pictures and post them to the “Battle for Brock” Facebook page along with an encouraging word or message of support from WOISD. Hashtags being used include #battleforbrock and #prayforbrock.
Brock’s mom is Paige Austin Gumm, who was a former White Oak student. Let us join together in the spirit of brotherhood and support for our neighbors, and former Roughneck. Being able to support others in a time of need is a large part of who we are and what we represent at WOISD.
It’s battle time, so get your blue on tomorrow!

(Blue shirts, pants, socks, hats, shoes are encouraged – no blue hair)

It's that time of year! It's time to start clipping those Box Tops, bagging them up, and sending them to school to help your classroom win one of the Box Top Contests. Students need to send their box tops in an envelope or in a baggie with the name of their teacher clearly marked. There will be one winner in each grade level.

Box Tops for Education is a program supported by General Mills and other companies that aid schools in raising money for various purchases and products they deem important for their students. For each Box Top we mail to General Mills, White Oak Intermediate will receive 10¢. We hope everyone will join in supporting our school and our kids with our 2017-2018 Box Top Contest.

SCHEDULE OF COMPETITION WEEKS LISTED IN TABLE.

For those who wish to participate, our annual food drive begins Monday, November 6th, and will end on Friday, November 10th. This event will aid the White Oak Temporary Assistance Program (TAP). Much needed are non-perishable items including canned meat, canned or dried fruit, pasta, spaghetti sauce, macaroni and cheese, soups, beans, and rice. They currently have ample supplies of green beans and corn.

We encourage the students to bring one food item. If every student brings just one, we will have more than 600 food items to donate! Thank you for your support.

Last week, the fifth grade honed in on some of their math strategies. One that they learned was PEMDAS. This math acronym, PEMDAS, is common. It stands for Parentheses, Exponents, Multiplication, Division, Addition, Subtraction. PEMDAS is often expanded to the mnemonic "Please Excuse My Dear Aunt Sally". Teachers used pizza as a reward for showing strategies (which is in the shape of a pizza slice.)

All of our fifth-grade students would like to send very special thank you to Sam Hassan at Moe's Pizza for donating the pizza for 5th grade. He does so much to support education and, especially, this community. Thank you, Mr. Hassan.

post_text: Parents, you MUST HAVE a White Oak Car Tag hanging in your vehicle in order to pick up your child(ren) via the Car Pickup Line. This procedure is for safety and efficiency. The car tag ensures the teacher calling for your student you have the authority to pick up that student. The car tag allows the teachers standing on the sidewalk with your child the ability to direct them safely and efficiently to your vehicle. If you do not have a car tag or if you have lost your car tag, please do not get in the pick up line. Park and come inside the building to pick up another tag before getting in the pick up line. If you get in the pick up line without the required car tag, the staff person calling cars will ask you to park and go inside to pick up a tag. They are available in the office. Thank you for working together with us to keep our boys and girls safe.

In the student handbook, we encourage parents not to drop off students before 7:30 for safety reasons. We do not have personnel on duty until 7:30 am. Therefore, students dropped off are left unsupervised. It has been reported that several students are horse playing near the steps leading down to the Primary parking lot. We are compelled to inform parents of the steep drop-off on the other side of the wall. As you can see from the pictures, should a student fall down the steps or off the edge of the wall, there could be a serious medical situation.

Your children are important to us and we want them arriving through our front doors at 7:30 safely. Please speak to your children about the dangers of this area and ways they can be safe.

post_text:
School will be closed Monday, September 4th. Enjoy the time with your families celebrating Labor Day. Talk to your children about Labor Day and what it means.

Labor Day is celebrated on the first Monday in September. It’s a day dedicated to the social and economic achievements of American workers. The holiday credits the contributions of the working class to the strength, prosperity, and well-being of our country.

Labor Day became an official national holiday in 1894. This holiday is usually celebrated with summer activities. Elementary teachers use this holiday to introduce the concept of Community Helpers to small children. Everyone plays a role or works a job that supports their community.

What role do you play in your community?

Pep rallies are typically held on Friday afternoons at 3:02 in the High School gym. Pep rally procedures are as follows:

If a student plans on attending the pep rally, the parent MUST send a note to the child’s teacher EACH WEEK. Students with NO NOTE will stay in the classroom and WILL NOT be called down until all of those with notes have been picked up FIRST. Teachers will keep the notes each week. Students will NOT be allowed to walk to the pep rally without an adult with them.
Only students who have a note will be sent to the cafeteria at 2:30.
The doors will remain locked until 2:30. Adults will enter through the Intermediate doors and sign their student out in the cafeteria.
Students who not picked up by 3:00 will be sent back to the classroom.
Again, students must be accompanied by an adult to attend the pep rally.
STUDENTS ATTENDING THE PEP RALLY ON FRIDAYS WILL MISS ALL OF THE FUN CLUB ACTIVITIES.

post_text:
Beginning September 1, 2017:

TEXTING BAN

It is an offense for an operator to use a portable wireless communication device:
To read, write, or send an electronic message while operating a motor vehicle unless the vehicle is stopped. (Section 545.4251, Transportation Code)

Persons under 18 years of age may not operate a motor vehicle while using a wireless communication device, except in case of emergency. This covers more than just electronic messaging. (Section 545.424, Transportation Code)
CHILD SAFETY SEATS

A person commits an offense if the person operates a passenger vehicle, transports a child who is younger than eight years of age, unless the child is taller than four feet, nine inches, and does not keep the child secured during the operation of the vehicle in a child passenger safety seat system according to the instructions of the manufacturer of the safety seat system. (Section 545.412, Transportation Code)

Yesterday, it took Intermediate 10-15 minutes tops to get all of the intermediate students either on the bus or in a car that was in the pickup line. Parents should not park and get out of their vehicles because students will not be dismissed except by these two procedures. This will only result in more time spent because it will be necessary for you to get back in the car pickup line.

If you would prefer for your child to ride a bus home instead of waiting in the long car pickup line, please contact Scott Stagner or let the Intermediate office know.
